We start by using the end‐of‐period values in each of the three statements.

1. Current Ratio:
 • Total Current Assets = 20,314,894.50 
 • Total Current Liabilities = 1,015,922.54  
  Current Ratio = 20,314,894.50 / 1,015,922.54 ≈ 20.00

2. Gross Profit Margin:
 • Gross Profit = 5,718,450.67  
 • Total Revenue = 20,318,450.67  
  Gross Profit Margin = (5,718,450.67 / 20,318,450.67) × 100 ≈ 28.15%

3. Debt to Asset Ratio:
 • Total Liabilities (from balance sheet, here equal to Total Current Liabilities) = 1,015,922.54  
 • Total Assets = 30,858,088.75  
  Debt to Asset Ratio = 1,015,922.54 / 30,858,088.75 ≈ 0.03

4. Net Profit Margin:
 • Net Profit = 1,842,166.21  
 • Total Revenue = 20,318,450.67  
  Net Profit Margin = (1,842,166.21 / 20,318,450.67) × 100 ≈ 9.07%

5. Cash to Current Debt Ratio:
 • Cash and Cash Equivalents: Sum of “Cash on Hand” and “Bank Deposits”. Here, Cash on Hand = –1,980,427.60 and Bank Deposits = 385,137.69. Their sum is –1,980,427.60 + 385,137.69 = –1,595,289.91  
 • Total Current Liabilities = 1,015,922.54  
  Cash to Current Debt Ratio = –1,595,289.91 / 1,015,922.54 ≈ –1.57

6. Free Cash Flow (FCF):
 • Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –18,924,462.44  
 • Capital Expenditures (the “Purchase of Fixed Assets”) = 2,670,827.47  
  FCF = Operating CF – CapEx = –18,924,462.44 – 2,670,827.47 = –21,595,289.91

7. Return on Assets (ROA):
 • Net Profit = 1,842,166.21  
 • Total Assets = 30,858,088.75  
  ROA = (1,842,166.21 / 30,858,088.75) × 100 ≈ 5.97%

The final answer is:

  }
}
